    <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
        
        Noorullah Shirzada/AFP via Getty Images
        
    </span>
</div>
<div class="enlarge_measure">
    <div class="img_wrap">
        <img data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/06/gettyimages-1204648012_wide-2056b165037654cacd12270da75de49d76eac23c-s1200.jpg" alt="" />
    </div>
</div>
<div class="enlarge_html">
    <div class="image_data">
        <p class="caption">Afghan Taliban militants and villagers celebrate the U.S. peace deal Monday in the Alingar district of Laghman Province. The group resumed offensive operations against Afghan security forces this week, ending a partial truce.</p>
        <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
            
            Noorullah Shirzada/AFP via Getty Images
            
        </span>
    </div>
</div>
   </div>
   <p>With less than four days to go before peace talks are to begin in Afghanistan between that nation's authorities and the Taliban insurgency, things are not looking promising.  </p>   <p>Taliban fighters are stepping up attacks on Afghan security forces. American warplanes are counterattacking. And a prisoner exchange that was to take place before those intra-Afghan talks start is being rejected by Afghan President Ashraf Ghani. </p>   <p>On Friday in western Kabul, the Associated Press reports that gunmen opened fire at a largely Shiite gathering, killing at least 32 and injuring scores more.  The Islamic State-Khorasan Province claimed <a href="http://thefortress.com.pk/islamic-state-claims-responsibility-for-kabul-attack-that-killed-27/">responsibility</a> for the attack.</p>   <p>All this comes after the U.S. and the Taliban — but not the Afghan government — signed an agreement Feb. 29 in Doha, Qatar with the stated aim of "bringing peace to Afghanistan" more than 18 years after U.S. forces pushed the Taliban out of power. </p>   <div id="res812963451" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage811276808" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/02/811276808/defense-secretary-gives-go-ahead-for-u-s-troops-to-start-afghan-drawdown"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/03\/02\/811276808\/defense-secretary-gives-go-ahead-for-u-s-troops-to-start-afghan-drawdown"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/02/esper_sq-717ebc9ebd1b82c0c82a5724b743c475d00ead99-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/02/esper_sq-717ebc9ebd1b82c0c82a5724b743c475d00ead99-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Defense Secretary Gives Go-Ahead For U.S. Troops To Start Afghan Drawdown" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/national-security/">National Security </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/02/811276808/defense-secretary-gives-go-ahead-for-u-s-troops-to-start-afghan-drawdown"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/03\/02\/811276808\/defense-secretary-gives-go-ahead-for-u-s-troops-to-start-afghan-drawdown"}' >Defense Secretary Gives Go-Ahead For U.S. Troops To Start Afghan Drawdown</a></h3>
